│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs in BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands during horizontal  │
│ reduction vectorization. The assertion checks that each instruction being     │
│ erased either has no users or all its users are already marked deleted. In    │
│ the reproducer, scalar compare instructions (%cmp80... and %tobool...) are    │
│ scheduled for deletion while they are still used by a chain of select         │
│ instructions implementing a boolean reduction. Those select instructions are  │
│ part of the reduction but are kept temporarily (they are placed in            │
│ UserIgnoreList). The validation code earlier (vectorizeTree) explicitly       │
│ allows erasing scalars whose users are in UserIgnoreList, but                 │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands' assertion does not account for this case. As a │
│ result, the assertion fires even though the situation is intended and handled │
│ elsewhere.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows lines such as:                                            │
│ SLP: \tvalidating user:  %cmp80.1.2.i.i = select ...                          │
│ SLP: \tErasing scalar:  %cmp80.1.2.i.i193 = icmp sgt i32 0, 0.                │
│ Similar patterns for other compares and boolean icmps. All scalar compares    │
│ are pushed into RemovedInsts. Their users (the select chain) remain alive and │
│ are not marked deleted. Because this is a horizontal reduction,               │
│ UserIgnoreList is active (set earlier when matching reduction). No            │
│ replacement of those select operands has yet occurred before                  │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands runs.                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ Code in vectorizeTree permits erasing scalars whose users are either          │
│ vectorized tree nodes, ignored reduction nodes (UserIgnoreList), or already   │
│ deleted. The assertion in removeInstructionsAndOperands only permits users    │
│ that are deleted (isDeleted). It omits the UserIgnoreList case. Thus, in      │
│ horizontal reduction mode, legitimate live users in UserIgnoreList trigger a  │
│ false assertion failure. The semantic expectation is that deletion of         │
│ underlying scalar instructions can proceed while reduction root/select nodes  │
│ are processed later; hence the assertion must allow users from UserIgnoreList │
│ similarly to the earlier validation.                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 2748-2753 in SLPVectorizer.cpp to extend the assertion predicate   │
│ to accept users contained in UserIgnoreList. This mirrors the earlier NDEBUG  │
│ check (lines ~16096-16102) and keeps consistency. Modified assertion:         │
│ assert((I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {                     │
│   if (auto *UsrI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()))                        │
│     return isDeleted(UsrI) || (UserIgnoreList &&                              │
│ UserIgnoreList->contains(UsrI));                                              │
│   return true; })) && "trying to erase instruction with users.");             │
│ This change preserves correctness while preventing the spurious abort.        │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: We are not weakening real safety because the pass logic            │
│ intentionally tolerates remaining users in UserIgnoreList (reduction tree     │
│ nodes) and will handle them later. The assertion was overly strict compared   │
│ to earlier validation logic and inconsistent with horizontal reduction flow.  │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By adjusting the assertion to recognize permitted remaining users (those in   │
│ UserIgnoreList), we align removeInstructionsAndOperands with the established  │
│ invariant used elsewhere in vectorizeTree. This prevents the abort for valid  │
│ reduction patterns like the reproducer while keeping the safety property that │
│ we do not erase instructions still used by arbitrary live IR outside the      │
│ managed reduction tree. No other logic changes required.                      │
│                                                                               │
