  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in
BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands during horizontal reduction vectorization.
The assertion checks that each instruction being erased either has no users or
all its users are already marked deleted. In the reproducer, scalar compare
instructions (%cmp80... and %tobool...) are scheduled for deletion while they are
still used by a chain of select instructions implementing a boolean reduction.
Those select instructions are part of the reduction but are kept temporarily
(they are placed in UserIgnoreList). The validation code earlier (vectorizeTree)
explicitly allows erasing scalars whose users are in UserIgnoreList, but
removeInstructionsAndOperands' assertion does not account for this case. As a
result, the assertion fires even though the situation is intended and handled
elsewhere.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows lines such as:\nSLP:
\\tvalidating user:  %cmp80.1.2.i.i = select ...\nSLP: \\tErasing scalar:
%cmp80.1.2.i.i193 = icmp sgt i32 0, 0.\nSimilar patterns for other compares and
boolean icmps. All scalar compares are pushed into RemovedInsts. Their users (the
select chain) remain alive and are not marked deleted. Because this is a
horizontal reduction, UserIgnoreList is active (set earlier when matching
reduction). No replacement of those select operands has yet occurred before
removeInstructionsAndOperands runs.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nCode in
vectorizeTree permits erasing scalars whose users are either vectorized tree
nodes, ignored reduction nodes (UserIgnoreList), or already deleted. The
assertion in removeInstructionsAndOperands only permits users that are deleted
(isDeleted). It omits the UserIgnoreList case. Thus, in horizontal reduction
mode, legitimate live users in UserIgnoreList trigger a false assertion failure.
The semantic expectation is that deletion of underlying scalar instructions can
proceed while reduction root/select nodes are processed later; hence the
assertion must allow users from UserIgnoreList similarly to the earlier
validation.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 2748-2753 in
SLPVectorizer.cpp to extend the assertion predicate to accept users contained in
UserIgnoreList. This mirrors the earlier NDEBUG check (lines ~16096-16102) and
keeps consistency. Modified assertion:\nassert((I->use_empty() ||
all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {\n  if (auto *UsrI =
dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()))\n    return isDeleted(UsrI) ||
(UserIgnoreList && UserIgnoreList->contains(UsrI));\n  return true; })) &&
\"trying to erase instruction with users.\");\nThis change preserves correctness
while preventing the spurious abort.\n\nRationale: We are not weakening real
safety because the pass logic intentionally tolerates remaining users in
UserIgnoreList (reduction tree nodes) and will handle them later. The assertion
was overly strict compared to earlier validation logic and inconsistent with
horizontal reduction flow.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adjusting the assertion to
recognize permitted remaining users (those in UserIgnoreList), we align
removeInstructionsAndOperands with the established invariant used elsewhere in
vectorizeTree. This prevents the abort for valid reduction patterns like the
reproducer while keeping the safety property that we do not erase instructions
still used by arbitrary live IR outside the managed reduction tree. No other
logic changes required.\n",
